						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">mikejmoffitt wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Koitsu, I thought the 68000's longword moves were performed as two 16-bit word moves with an auto-increment. Is there really a substantial speed difference?</div><br />Don't know -- I know jack squat about the 68000.  All I did was read some documentation/web pages describing the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">move</tt> opcode: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://mrjester.hapisan.com/04_MC68/Sect01Part05/Index.html">http://mrjester.hapisan.com/04_MC68/Sec ... Index.html</a><!-- m --><br /><br />How I interpret the information shown there: <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">.b</tt> uses bytes (8 bits), <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">.w</tt> uses words (16 bits), and <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">.l</tt> uses &quot;long word&quot; (32 bits).  How this is implemented internally (e.g. <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">move.l</tt> might move two 16-bit words (high word, then low word)) is irrelevant to me because the end result would be the same (32 bits of data got moved).  Is that not correct?</div>

